[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[ab}Why the King of France is so suddenly gone back know you no reason?{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[ab}Something he left imperfect in the state, which since his coming forth is thought of, which imports to the kingdom so much fear and danger that his personal return was most required and necessary.{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[ab}Who hath he left behind him general?{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[ab}The Marshal of France, Monsieur La Far.{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[ab}Did your letters pierce the Queen to any demonstration of grief?{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.12{]}Ay, sir, she took them, read them in my{line] 
[line [n}4.3.13{]}presence,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.14{]}And now and then an ample tear trilled down{line] 
[line [n}4.3.15{]}Her delicate cheek. It seemed she was a queen{line] 
[line [n}4.3.16{]}Over her passion, who, most rebel-like,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.17{]}Fought to be king o’er her.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.18{]}O, then it moved her.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.19{]}Not to a rage. Patience and sorrow strove{line] 
[line [n}4.3.20{]}Who should express her goodliest. You have seen{line] 
[line [n}4.3.21{]}Sunshine and rain at once; her smiles and tears{line] 
[line [n}4.3.22{]}Were like a better way. Those happy smilets{line] 
[line [n}4.3.23{]}That played on her ripe lip seemed not to know{line] 
[line [n}4.3.24{]}What guests were in her eyes, which parted thence{line] 
[line [n}4.3.25{]}As pearls from diamonds dropped. In brief,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.26{]}Sorrow would be a rarity most beloved{line] 
[line [n}4.3.27{]}If all could so become it.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.28{]}Made she no verbal question?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.29{]}Faith, once or twice she heaved the name of{line] [q}
[line [n}4.3.30{]}father{line]{q] 
[line [n}4.3.31{]}Pantingly forth, as if it pressed her heart;{line] 
[line [n}4.3.32{]}Cried [q}Sisters, sisters, shame of ladies, sisters!{line] 
[line [n}4.3.33{]}Kent, father, sisters! What, i’ th’ storm, i’ th’ night?{line] 
[line [n}4.3.34{]}Let pity not be believed!{q] There she shook{line] 
[line [n}4.3.35{]}The holy water from her heavenly eyes,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.36{]}And clamor moistened. Then away she started,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.37{]}To deal with grief alone.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.38{]}It is the stars.{line] 
[line [n}4.3.39{]}The stars above us govern our conditions,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.40{]}Else one self mate and make could not beget{line] 
[line [n}4.3.41{]}Such different issues. You spoke not with her{line] 
[line [n}4.3.42{]}since?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[ab}No.{ab] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.44{]}Was this before the King returned?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.45{]}No, since.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.46{]}Well, sir, the poor distressèd Lear’s i’ th’ town,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.47{]}Who sometime in his better tune remembers{line] 
[line [n}4.3.48{]}What we are come about, and by no means{line] 
[line [n}4.3.49{]}Will yield to see his daughter.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.50{]}Why, good sir?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.51{]}A sovereign shame so elbows him—his own{line] 
[line [n}4.3.52{]}unkindness,{line] 
[line [n}4.3.53{]}That stripped her from his benediction, turned her{line] 
[line [n}4.3.54{]}To foreign casualties, gave her dear rights{line] 
[line [n}4.3.55{]}To his dog-hearted daughters—these things sting{line] 
[line [n}4.3.56{]}His mind so venomously that burning shame{line] 
[line [n}4.3.57{]}Detains him from Cordelia.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.58{]}Alack, poor gentleman!{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.59{]}Of Albany’s and Cornwall’s powers you heard not?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GENTLEMAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.3.60{]}’Tis so. They are afoot.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}KENT{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.3.61{]}Well, sir, I’ll bring you to our master Lear{line] 
[line [n}4.3.62{]}And leave you to attend him. Some dear cause{line] 
[line [n}4.3.63{]}Will in concealment wrap me up awhile.{line] 
[line [n}4.3.64{]}When I am known aright, you shall not grieve{line] 
[line [n}4.3.65{]}Lending me this acquaintance. I pray you, go{line] 
[line [n}4.3.66{]}Along with me.{line] {sp] 
[stage [n}SD 4.3.66.1{][}They exit.{]] {scene]
[scene [n}4{][head}Scene 4{head]}
[stage [n}SD 4.4.0{][}Enter with Drum and Colors, Cordelia, Doctor, Gentlemen, and Soldiers.{]]  
[sp [speaker}CORDELIA{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.4.1{]}Alack, ’tis he! Why, he was met even now{line] 
[line [n}4.4.2{]}As mad as the vexed sea, singing aloud,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.3{]}Crowned with rank fumiter and furrow-weeds,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.4{]}With hardocks, hemlock, nettles, cuckooflowers,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.5{]}Darnel, and all the idle weeds that grow{line] 
[line [n}4.4.6{]}In our sustaining corn. A century send forth.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.7{]}Search every acre in the high-grown field{line] 
[line [n}4.4.8{]}And bring him to our eye.{line]
[stage [n}SD 4.4.8{][}Soldiers exit.{]] 
[line [n}4.4.9{]}What can man’s wisdom{line] 
[line [n}4.4.10{]}In the restoring his bereavèd sense?{line] 
[line [n}4.4.11{]}He that helps him take all my outward worth.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}DOCTOR{speaker]}
[line [n}4.4.12{]}There is means, madam.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.13{]}Our foster nurse of nature is repose,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.14{]}The which he lacks. That to provoke in him{line] 
[line [n}4.4.15{]}Are many simples operative, whose power{line] 
[line [n}4.4.16{]}Will close the eye of anguish.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}CORDELIA{speaker]}
[line [n}4.4.17{]}All blest secrets,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.18{]}All you unpublished virtues of the earth,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.19{]}Spring with my tears. Be aidant and remediate{line] 
[line [n}4.4.20{]}In the good man’s distress. Seek, seek for him,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.21{]}Lest his ungoverned rage dissolve the life{line] 
[line [n}4.4.22{]}That wants the means to lead it.{line] {sp]  
[stage [n}SD 4.4.22.1{][}Enter Messenger.{]]  
[sp [speaker}MESSENGER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.4.23{]}News, madam.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.24{]}The British powers are marching hitherward.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}CORDELIA{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.4.25{]}’Tis known before. Our preparation stands{line] 
[line [n}4.4.26{]}In expectation of them.—O dear father,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.27{]}It is thy business that I go about.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.28{]}Therefore great France{line] 
[line [n}4.4.29{]}My mourning and importuned tears hath pitied.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.30{]}No blown ambition doth our arms incite,{line] 
[line [n}4.4.31{]}But love, dear love, and our aged father’s right.{line] 
[line [n}4.4.32{]}Soon may I hear and see him.{line] {sp] 
[stage [n}SD 4.4.32.1{][}They exit.{]] {scene]
[scene [n}5{][head}Scene 5{head]}
[stage [n}SD 4.5.0{][}Enter Regan and Oswald, the Steward.{]]  
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.1{]}But are my brother’s powers set forth?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.2{]}Ay, madam.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.3{]}Himself in person there?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.4{]}Madam, with much ado.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.5{]}Your sister is the better soldier.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.6{]}Lord Edmund spake not with your lord at home?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.7{]}No, madam.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.8{]}What might import my sister’s letter to him?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.9{]}I know not, lady.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.10{]}Faith, he is posted hence on serious matter.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.11{]}It was great ignorance, Gloucester’s eyes being out,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.12{]}To let him live. Where he arrives he moves{line] 
[line [n}4.5.13{]}All hearts against us. Edmund, I think, is gone,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.14{]}In pity of his misery, to dispatch{line] 
[line [n}4.5.15{]}His nighted life; moreover to descry{line] 
[line [n}4.5.16{]}The strength o’ th’ enemy.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.17{]}I must needs after him, madam, with my letter.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.18{]}Our troops set forth tomorrow. Stay with us.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.19{]}The ways are dangerous.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.20{]}I may not, madam.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.21{]}My lady charged my duty in this business.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.22{]}Why should she write to Edmund? Might not you{line] 
[line [n}4.5.23{]}Transport her purposes by word? Belike,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.24{]}Some things—I know not what. I’ll love thee much—{line] 
[line [n}4.5.25{]}Let me unseal the letter.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.26{]}Madam, I had rather—{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.27{]}I know your lady does not love her husband;{line] 
[line [n}4.5.28{]}I am sure of that; and at her late being here,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.29{]}She gave strange eliads and most speaking looks{line] 
[line [n}4.5.30{]}To noble Edmund. I know you are of her bosom.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.31{]}I, madam?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.32{]}I speak in understanding. Y’ are; I know ’t.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.33{]}Therefore I do advise you take this note:{line] 
[line [n}4.5.34{]}My lord is dead; Edmund and I have talked,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.35{]}And more convenient is he for my hand{line] 
[line [n}4.5.36{]}Than for your lady’s. You may gather more.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.37{]}If you do find him, pray you, give him this,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.38{]}And when your mistress hears thus much from you,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.39{]}I pray, desire her call her wisdom to her.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.40{]}So, fare you well.{line] 
[line [n}4.5.41{]}If you do chance to hear of that blind traitor,{line] 
[line [n}4.5.42{]}Preferment falls on him that cuts him off.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}OSWALD{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.5.43{]}Would I could meet him, madam. I should show{line] 
[line [n}4.5.44{]}What party I do follow.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}REGAN{speaker]}
[line [n}4.5.45{]}Fare thee well.{line] {sp] 
[stage [n}SD 4.5.45.1{][}They exit.{]] {scene]
[scene [n}6{][head}Scene 6{head]}
[stage [n}SD 4.6.0{][}Enter Gloucester and Edgar dressed as a peasant.{]]  
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.1{]}When shall I come to th’ top of that same hill?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.2{]}You do climb up it now. Look how we labor.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.3{]}Methinks the ground is even.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.4{]}Horrible steep.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.5{]}Hark, do you hear the sea?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.6{]}No, truly.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.7{]}Why then, your other senses grow imperfect{line] 
[line [n}4.6.8{]}By your eyes’ anguish.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.9{]}So may it be indeed.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.10{]}Methinks thy voice is altered and thou speak’st{line] 
[line [n}4.6.11{]}In better phrase and matter than thou didst.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.12{]}You’re much deceived; in nothing am I changed{line] 
[line [n}4.6.13{]}But in my garments.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.14{]}Methinks you’re better spoken.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.15{]}Come on, sir. Here’s the place. Stand still. How{line] 
[line [n}4.6.16{]}fearful{line] 
[line [n}4.6.17{]}And dizzy ’tis to cast one’s eyes so low!{line] 
[line [n}4.6.18{]}The crows and choughs that wing the midway air{line] 
[line [n}4.6.19{]}Show scarce so gross as beetles. Halfway down{line] 
[line [n}4.6.20{]}Hangs one that gathers samphire—dreadful trade;{line] 
[line [n}4.6.21{]}Methinks he seems no bigger than his head.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.22{]}The fishermen that walk upon the beach{line] 
[line [n}4.6.23{]}Appear like mice, and yond tall anchoring bark{line] 
[line [n}4.6.24{]}Diminished to her cock, her cock a buoy{line] 
[line [n}4.6.25{]}Almost too small for sight. The murmuring surge{line] 
[line [n}4.6.26{]}That on th’ unnumbered idle pebble chafes{line] 
[line [n}4.6.27{]}Cannot be heard so high. I’ll look no more{line] 
[line [n}4.6.28{]}Lest my brain turn and the deficient sight{line] 
[line [n}4.6.29{]}Topple down headlong.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.30{]}Set me where you stand.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.31{]}Give me your hand. You are now within a foot{line] 
[line [n}4.6.32{]}Of th’ extreme verge. For all beneath the moon{line] 
[line [n}4.6.33{]}Would I not leap upright.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.34{]}Let go my hand.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.35{]}Here, friend, ’s another purse; in it a jewel{line] 
[line [n}4.6.36{]}Well worth a poor man’s taking. Fairies and gods{line] 
[line [n}4.6.37{]}Prosper it with thee.{line]
[stage [n}SD 4.6.37{][}He gives Edgar a purse.{]] 
[line [n}4.6.38{]}Go thou further off.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.39{]}Bid me farewell, and let me hear thee going.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[stage [run-in] [n}SD 4.6.40.0{][}, walking away{]] 
[line [n}4.6.40{]}Now fare you well, good sir.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.41{]}With all my heart.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[stage [run-in] [n}SD 4.6.42.0{][}, aside{]] 
[line [n}4.6.42{]}Why I do trifle thus with his despair{line] 
[line [n}4.6.43{]}Is done to cure it.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.44{]}O you mighty gods!{line]
[stage [n}SD 4.6.44{][}He kneels.{]] 
[line [n}4.6.45{]}This world I do renounce, and in your sights{line] 
[line [n}4.6.46{]}Shake patiently my great affliction off.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.47{]}If I could bear it longer, and not fall{line] 
[line [n}4.6.48{]}To quarrel with your great opposeless wills,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.49{]}My snuff and loathèd part of nature should{line] 
[line [n}4.6.50{]}Burn itself out. If Edgar live, O, bless him!—{line] 
[line [n}4.6.51{]}Now, fellow, fare thee well.{line] {sp]
[stage [n}SD 4.6.51{][}He falls.{]] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.52{]}Gone, sir. Farewell.—{line] 
[line [n}4.6.53{]}And yet I know not how conceit may rob{line] 
[line [n}4.6.54{]}The treasury of life, when life itself{line] 
[line [n}4.6.55{]}Yields to the theft. Had he been where he thought,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.56{]}By this had thought been past. Alive or dead?—{line] 
[line [n}4.6.57{]}Ho you, sir! Friend, hear you. Sir, speak.—{line] 
[line [n}4.6.58{]}Thus might he pass indeed. Yet he revives.—{line] 
[line [n}4.6.59{]}What are you, sir?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.60{]}Away, and let me die.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.61{]}Hadst thou been aught but gossamer, feathers, air,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.62{]}So many fathom down precipitating,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.63{]}Thou [app [from}#c0423920{]}[rdg [wit}#print #ebook{]]{app]’dst shivered like an egg; but thou dost{line] 
[line [n}4.6.64{]}breathe,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.65{]}Hast heavy substance, bleed’st not, speak’st, art{line] 
[line [n}4.6.66{]}sound.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.67{]}Ten masts at each make not the altitude{line] 
[line [n}4.6.68{]}Which thou hast perpendicularly fell.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.69{]}Thy life’s a miracle. Speak yet again.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.70{]}But have I fall’n or no?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.71{]}From the dread summit of this chalky bourn.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.72{]}Look up a-height. The shrill-gorged lark so far{line] 
[line [n}4.6.73{]}Cannot be seen or heard. Do but look up.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.74{]}Alack, I have no eyes.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.75{]}Is wretchedness deprived that benefit{line] 
[line [n}4.6.76{]}To end itself by death? ’Twas yet some comfort{line] 
[line [n}4.6.77{]}When misery could beguile the tyrant’s rage{line] 
[line [n}4.6.78{]}And frustrate his proud will.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.79{]}Give me your arm.{line] 
[stage [n}SD 4.6.79.1{][}He raises Gloucester.{]] 
[line [n}4.6.80{]}Up. So, how is ’t? Feel you your legs? You stand.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.81{]}Too well, too well.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.82{]}This is above all strangeness.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.83{]}Upon the crown o’ th’ cliff, what thing was that{line] 
[line [n}4.6.84{]}Which parted from you?{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]}
[line [n}4.6.85{]}A poor unfortunate beggar.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.86{]}As I stood here below, methought his eyes{line] 
[line [n}4.6.87{]}Were two full moons; he had a thousand noses,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.88{]}Horns whelked and waved like the enragèd sea.{line] 
[line [n}4.6.89{]}It was some fiend. Therefore, thou happy father,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.90{]}Think that the clearest gods, who make them{line] 
[line [n}4.6.91{]}honors{line] 
[line [n}4.6.92{]}Of men’s impossibilities, have preserved thee.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}GLOUCESTER{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.93{]}I do remember now. Henceforth I’ll bear{line] 
[line [n}4.6.94{]}Affliction till it do cry out itself{line] [q}
[line [n}4.6.95{]}Enough, enough!{q] and die. That thing you speak of,{line] 
[line [n}4.6.96{]}I took it for a man. Often ’twould say{line] [q}
[line [n}4.6.97{]}The fiend, the fiend!{q] He led me to that place.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}EDGAR{speaker]} 
[line [n}4.6.98{]}Bear free and patient thoughts.{line]  
[stage [n}SD 4.6.98.1{][}Enter Lear.{]]  
[line [n}4.6.99{]}But who comes here?{line] 
[line [n}4.6.100{]}The safer sense will ne’er accommodate{line] 
[line [n}4.6.101{]}His master thus.{line] {sp] 
[sp [speaker}LEAR{speaker]}
